ce:section.ce:para:
CuNPs deposited on NCDs were prepared via a one-pot DMF-based reduction approach without any additives. DMF acts here as a multifunctional reagent, serving as reducing agent, stabilizer, and solvent. The influence of the copper source i.e., CuNPs or CuCl2 on the deposition of CuNPs onto the NCDs was investigated (Scheme 1
                        ), and the synthesized materials will be, hereafter, designated as CuNPs/NCDs and CuCl2/NCDs, respectively. The amount of copper metal present in both materials was determined using inductively coupled plasma-atomic emission spectroscopy (ICP-AES, Fig. 1
                        (a) and Table S1). The CuNPs/NCDs had a Cu content of 39.64 ppm (0.396 wt%), which is almost twice that of the CuCl2/NCDs (22.81 ppm, 0.233 wt%). The higher amount of Cu indicates that DMF-protected CuNPs are effective as a precursor for the preparation of CuNPs on NCDs. In contrast, our recent work demonstrated that CuCl2 is an appropriate precursor for the preparation of CuNPs/rGO, as shown by the high Cu content in CuNPs/rGO [26]. It was proposed that the oxygen-containing functional groups contribute the adsorption of metal ions on the surface of GO via coordination, hence, facilitating the fabrication of Cu species on the GO surface. For N-doped carbon materials, the presence of N dopants in carbon matrices can stabilize Cu ions via the coordination interaction, suppressing severe agglomeration of Cu clusters [16,17]. Therefore, we hypothesized that using DMF-protected CuNPs might be an appropriate source of Cu to fabricate CuNPs-decorated NCDs.
